About Care Check-In
Short patient surveys are conducted on the AirSense 11 and myAir app to better understand how
the patient is doing with therapy. If the patient consents, we can share Care Check-In information
through AirView for clinical users.

Questions and answers
At the beginning of therapy, the patient is asked a baseline question. A few additional questions are
asked, about once per week, during the early stages of therapy. For example:

How sleepy did you feel this week? Extremely, Very, Moderately, Slightly, Not at all.

How is your therapy? Great, OK, Challenging.

What bothers you most? Getting used to therapy, Fitting the mask, Using the machine.

Please rate your usual sleep quality. Very poor, Poor, OK, Good, Excellent

How was your sleep quality in the last week? Very poor, Poor, OK, Good, Excellent

Medications: cinnamon, milk thistle, fish oil, simvastatin, lisinopril, hydrochlorothiazide, glucosamine, aspirin 81 mg,

## ipratropium bromide

The PSG (polysomnogram) is the continuous and simultaneous monitoring and recording of the physiological parameters of sleep for six or more

hours with a physician review and interpretations. The following parameters were used: F3-M2, F4- M1, C3-M2, C4-M1, O2-M1, O1-M2, ROC-M1,

LOC-M2, Chin EMG, RAT, LAT, nasal pressure, thermistor snore sensor, RIP (chest, abdomen), pulse oximetry, body position. All scoring follows

the recommendations of the American Academy of Sleep Medicine. The AHI (Apnea Hypopneas Index) is the number of apneas and hypopneas

with a 4% desaturation per hour of sleep (CMS requirement). Central hypopnea: 30-90% reduction in oronasal airflow for at least 10 seconds,

associated with 30- 90% in-phase reduction of thoracoabdominal movement, followed by oxygen desaturation of at least 4%. The event should not

be scored as central in the presence of snoring or increase in submental EMG activity.

About Care Check-In
Short patient surveys are conducted on the AirSense 11 and myAir app to better understand how
the patient is doing with therapy. If the patient consents, we can share Care Check-In information
through AirView for clinical users.
Questions and answers
At the beginning of therapy, the patient is asked a baseline question. A few additional questions are
asked, about once per week, during the early stages of therapy. For example:
How sleepy did you feel this week?  Extremely, Very, Moderately, Slightly, Not at all.
How is your therapy?  Great, OK, Challenging.

the  recommendations

 and  hypopneas
with  a 4%  desaturation

. Central  hypopnea:

 airflow for at least  10  seconds,
associated with 30- 90%  in-phase  reduction  of thoracoabdominal
 movement, followed  by oxygen  desaturation
 of at least  4%. The  event  should  not
be  scored  as  central  in the  presence
 of snoring  or increase  in submental
 EMG activity.

About Care Check-In
Short patient surveys are conducted on the AirSense 11 and myAir app to better understand how
the patient is doing with therapy. If the patient consents, we can share Care Check-In information
through AirView for clinical users.

Questions and answers
At the beginning of therapy, the patient is asked a baseline question. A few additional questions are
asked, about once per week, during the early stages of therapy. For example:

How sleepy did you feel this week?  Extremely, Very, Moderately, Slightly, Not at all.

How is your therapy?  Great, OK, Challenging.

What bothers you most?  Getting used to therapy, Fitting the mask, Using the machine.

Please rate your usual sleep quality.  Very poor, Poor, OK, Good, Excellent

About Care Check-In
Short patient surveys are conducted on the AirSense 11 and myAir app to better understand how
the patient is doing with therapy. If the patient consents, we can share Care Check-In information
through AirView for clinical users.

Questions and answers
At the beginning of therapy, the patient is asked a baseline question. A few additional questions are
asked, about once per week, during the early stages of therapy. For example:

How sleepy did you feel this week?  Extremely, Very, Moderately, Slightly, Not at all.

How is your therapy?  Great, OK, Challenging.

What bothers you most?  Getting used to therapy, Fitting the mask, Using the machine.

# Diagnosis

# Treatment Options

Standard for treatment of OSA: Treatment options for patients with obstructive sleep apnea include mandibular advancing device. Further options may include positive airway pressure which remains the gold standard surgical interventions with OSA and including hypoglossal nerve stimulation for patients with the impact of sedating medications.

# General Recommendations

Maintaining a healthy weight, avoiding weight gain. General sleep counseling for patients on stimulant implant and weight loss. Avoiding drowsy driving. Obstructive sleep apnea includes: avoiding sleep in every 24-hour period for adults.

# Testing Type & Methods

Type of Test: Diagnostic PSG

Method: Polysomnography was conducted on the night of 6/22/2023.

The following parameters were monitored: Frontal, central and occipital EEG, electroculogram (EOG), submentalis EMG, nasal and oral airflow, anterior tibialis EMG, body position and electrocardiogram. Additionally, thoracic and abdominal movements were recorded by inductance plethysmography. Oxygen saturation (spO2) was monitored using a pulse oximeter. The tracing was scored using 30 second epochs. Hypopneas were scored per AASM definition.

A Central Apnea was defined as a cessation of oral and nasal airflow with simultaneous cessations of respiratory movements for at least 10 seconds (2 respiratory cycles in children); An Obstructive Apnea was defined as a cessation of airflow for at least 10 seconds (2 respiratory cycles in children).

# Brief Clinical History

This Patient is a 44 year old Male who underwent a diagnostic polysomnogram in an effort to determine the etiology of the patient's complaints of excessive daytime somnolence; loud snoring and frequent arousals from sleep.

# Sleep Data:

The study began at 9:48:48 PM. The patient was monitored for a total of 449.5 minutes, out of which the patient slept for 346.5 minutes: Sleep onset occurred at 11:09:47 PM for a sleep latency of 81.0 minutes. REM latency was 106.5 minutes. Wake After Sleep Onset (WASO) was 22.0 minutes. The study ended at 5:18:25 AM.

About Care Check-In

Short patient surveys are conducted on the AirSense 11 and myAir app to better understand how
the patient is doing with therapy. If the patient consents, we can share Care Check-In information

At the beginning of therapy, the patient is asked a baseline question. A few additional questions are
asked, about once per week, during the early stages of therapy. For example:

Testing Type & Methods
Type of Test: Diagnostic PSG

Method: Polysomnography was conducted on the night of 6/22/2023. The following parameters were monitored:
Frontal, central and occipital EEG, electroculogram (EOG}, submentalis EMG, nasal and oral airflow, anterior tibialis
EMG, body position and electrocard iogram. Additionally, thoracic and abdominal movements were recorded by
inductance plethysmography. Oxygen saturation (spO02) was monitored using a pulse oximeter, The tracing was
scored using 30 second epochs. Hypopneas were scored per AASM definition.

A Central Apnea was defined as a cessation of oral and nasal airflow with simultaneous cessations of respiratory
movements for at least 10 seconds (2 respiratory cycles in children).

An Obstructive Apnea was defined as a cessation of airflow for at least 10 seconds (2 respiratory cycles in children)
in the presence of continuous respiratory movements.

Hypopneas were scored per AASM definition.
